Photo by @amivitale. The divine Hamsini. Hamsini was rescued from a well when she was a year old in May 2019. She is cared for by the team at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e ) in northern Kenya. As the drought here continues, the dropping water table means that the wells are getting deeper and deeper. This makes it increasingly harder for elephants to get to the water and more likely for baby elephants like Hamsini to fall in and be orphaned. 

My new film "Shaba" tells the extraordinary story of Reteti's first matriarch. Ticket sales go directly to support orphaned elephants like Hamsini and her incredible keepers. It will be available on-demand until August 31. Visit shabafilm.org or click on the link in my profile to watch today.

Video by @amivitale. The orphans at Reteti drink 2 liter bottles of milk every three hours, around the clock. Each bottle is specially formulated for the particular nutritional needs of each baby elephant. In between feeds bottles are sterilized, the kitchen is cleaned and the next feed is prepared. All this is done while keeping a close eye on the elephants and showering them with love and care. The milk itself is sourced from the local community and its production is owned and managed by women, meaning it's both sustainably produced and supports both women's empowerment and the people who live here.

When you buy a ticket to see my new film, Shaba, you are buying a bottle of milk for one of these infants. 100% of ticket sales go directly to @r.e.s.c.u.e.  Your purchase ripples out, nourishing elephants and creating a brighter future for the community surrounding and caring for them. And now, thanks to a generous anonymous donor, the next $10,000 in contributions will be doubled. buying a ticket or by donating directly to @r.e.s.c.u.e. Visit shabafilm.org today and make a difference. A whole herd of elephants will thank you. Please share!!!

Video by @amivitale. Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) keeper Naomi sings to the orphaned baby elephants in her care as she leaves for the day. Naomi was one of the first indigenous Samburu women elephant keepers.  Today Reteti has a total of seven women keepers and their work has made them role models in their own community and around the world. 

My new film "Shaba" tells the extraordinary story of one of the orphans in her care. Ticket sales go directly to support the elephants and their incredible keepers. It is available on-demand until August 31. Visit shabafilm.org or click on the link in my profile to watch today.

Photo by @amivitale Calling ALL ocean photographers! The entry period for this year’s @ocean_photography_awards closes at midnight today! 

The Awards are a celebration of our beautiful blue planet, as well as a platform to highlight the many plights the ocean is facing. Last year’s winning images reached more than 500 million people, creating a ripple of connection and conversation across the world - all around the striking ocean art you create. 

If you’ve not been in the water much in the last 18 months, don’t worry - your submissions don’t have to be new photographs, they just can’t have won another award. And best of all, every entrant is a conservationist: 100% of your entry fee supports the amazing conservation work I’m proud to be a part of at @sealegacy. 

As a judge this year, I can’t wait to see your work. Good luck! 

Share your passion. Be the change. 

 . ENTER TODAY at oceanographicmagazine.com/OPA (link in bio)
#oceanphotographyawards #oceanphotographeroftheyear #conservation #exploration #adventure

Photo by @amivitale. Breaking news!! THREE more northern white rhino embryos have been created this month by @biorescue_project, the global team of scientists and conservationists working to save the species from extinction at @olpejeta conservancy in northern Kenya. This brings the total to TWELVE embryos. This time they were able to use sperm from Angalifu, improving the genetic diversity of the embryos. 

Head rhino keeper @zacharia443 sits with Najin, one of the last 2 northern white rhinos before the operation (1). The scientists and conservationists of Leibniz Institute for Zoo and Wildlife Research (@leibnizizw), @SafariParkDvurKralove @KenyaWildlifeService @OlPejeta Conservancy and #Avantea conducted this sixth successful oocyte collection on July 9 (2). Prof. Dr. Thomas Hildebrandt of @leibnizizw meticulously looks for the oocytes with Susanne Holtze (3-4). Frank Goeritz checks on Fatu while she is anesthetized (5). KWS Veterinarian Domnic Mijele, Ol Pejeta Vet Stephen Ngulu and Frank Goeritz in the operation (6). Immediately after the oocyte retrieval, the 17 eggs were airlifted accompanied by Dr. Hildebrandt (7) to Avantea laboratory in Cremona, Italy for maturation, fertilization, embryo development and cryopreservation. Two embryos were produced using semen from northern white rhino bull Suni, who has provided the genetics for all the existing embryos; the third embryo was from Angalifu.  TWELVE pure northern white rhino embryos await implantation in southern white rhino surrogates, a step expected to begin by the end of 2021. 

Owuan is the sterilized southern white rhino bull who will serve as the oestrus detector for the females as they come into season. (9)

Ariemet (19yo) and Mojo (11yo) are southern white rhino surrogates who will carry the northern white rhino embryos. Neither Najin nor Fatu are able to carry a pregnancy.  Both southern white rhino surrogates have successfully carried before. Ariemet has 4 calves and Mojo, 1. (10)

Learn more, including how to help, by following @biorescue_project.
